and controversy and continues to be so today. As the cases in this volume show, already in Antiquity, Greeks, Romans, Jews and Christians clashed over male circumcision. Then as now, concerns about identity, ritual, health, masculinity, and sexuality were a factor in these disputes. Very little is known about actual circumcision practices in the ancient world. Apart from depictions in art, the relation of which to daily practice is difficult to ascertain, we have historical access mainly through texts that reveal how the practice was discursively constructed, and that relate circumcision to wider cultural practices and ideas. This book therefore mainly discusses references to circumcision in literary sources, and the way these relate to other known cultural practices and ideas. These sources date from biblical times and Antiquity and their interpretations in medieval Jewish texts and recent scholarship.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aRELIGION / Judaism / General.2bisacsh1 aBecking, Bob, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarrocks, Rebecca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoorthy, Asha K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNeutel, Karin B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNeutel, Karin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNikolsky, Ronit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmit, Peter-Ben, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTeugels, Lieve M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTeugels, Lieve, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus PP Package 2023 Part 2z978311117804208iTitle is pa